## Gurobi'de problem çözme

Gubobi'de problem çözmek için problemi bir Gurobi modelinde soyutlamak gerekiyor. .NET entegrasyonunda bu model GRBModel nesnesinde oluşturuluyor. Model temel olarak değişkenler ve bu değişkenlerin kullanıldığı eşitliklerden oluşuyor. Ayrıca modelin hedefini, yani maksimize ya da minimize edilmek istenen değişken ya da ifadeyi modelde belirtebiliyoruz. Modeldeki değişken ve eşitlikleri, optimizasyon hedefini ve optimizasyon parametrelerini (örneğin model çözülürken bulunan üst sınır optimum değere ne kadar yakınken aramayı bıraksın) verdikten sonra Optimize method'unu çağırarak problem çözümünü başlatıyoruz. Bu method bittkten sonra model'in Status property'si ile bir çözüm bulunup bulunamadığını anlayabiliyoruz. Eğer bir çözüm bulunmuşsa değişkenlerin optimum değerlerini Get mehoduyla çekebiliyoruz.

## GAMS

General Algebraic Modeling System (GAMS) problemi modellerken 'nın kullanmayı tercih ettiği platform. Solver olarak Gurobi dahil farklı engine'ler kullanabiliyor. Gurobinin doğrudan desteklemediği vektorel eşitlikleri, vektörel değişkenler ve parametreler üzerinde index bazlı şartlı ifadeleri destekliyor. GAMS, temel olarak kendi modelleme dilinde yazılmış bir modeli kullandığı engine'e aktarıp sonuçlarını alıyor. Bizim EHM projesinde yaptığımız da benzer şekilde Maps.SolverModel objeleriyle soyutlanmış problemi Gurobi modeline aktarıp sonuçları almak oldu.

### public class IndexModifier

Bir Set üzerinde tanımlanır, eklendiği Term türlerinde, değerlendirme sırasında bağlamdaki index değerinin ne kadar arttırılıp azaltılacağını belirler. Örneğin GAMS notasyonuyla:

```

```

Equation'ındaki *inventory(s, t-1)* Term'i bir VectorTerm ile ifade edilirken, t-1 index'ini ifade etmek için bağlamdaki t Set'i index'ine -1 ekleyen bir IndexModifier kullanılır.

IndexModifier'ın bir başka kullanım alanı da, bağlamda tanımlı bir Alias ile kullanılması istenen vektörel değişken ya da parametrelerin, OrdinalityCondiitonTerm'lerin hangi index'i kullanması gerektiğini belirlemek içindir. Örneğin:

```
sales6(s,t,p,b).. w(s,t,p) + w(s,t,p+1) + 2*(y(s,t,b)$(ord(b) ne ord(p) and ord(b) ne ord(p)-1)) =l= 2;
```

s,t,p,b).. w(s,t,p) + w(s,t,p+1) + 2*(y(s,t,b)$(ord(b) ne ord(p) and ord(b) ne ord(p)-1)) =l= 2;
```

Equation'ında b, p isimli Set'in bir Alias'ı. y(s,t,p) ise p Set'i üzerine tanımlanmış bir değişken. Burada y(s,t,b) teriminin bağlamdaki b index'ini kullanmasını sağlamak için bir IndexModifier kullanılır.

Gurobi_UseInstantCloud true ise IC kullanılır, değilse lokal makinadaki Gurobi kullanılır. Lokal Gurobi kullanılacaksa bir Gurobi lisansının lokal makinaya kurulmuş olması gerekir.

Multithreaded true ise her web service client'ı için ayrı Engine kullanılır. Değilse tek Engine tüm client'lardan gelen modelleri geliş sırasıyla çözer.

Gurobi_CloudId ve Gurobi_CloudKey Gurobi IC isteklerinde kullanılan ID ve istekleri imzalamak için kullanılan secret key'dir. Güvenlik amacıyla TFS'de ve burada yer almıyor. Şuradan edinebilirsiniz: [https://cloud.gurobi.com/app](https://cloud.gurobi.com/app)

Bunların dışındaki parametrelerden Gurobi_LicenseType dışındakilerin anlamları isimlerinden açıktır. Gurobi_LicenseType iki değer alabilir: "light compute server" ve "full compute server". Light lisans ile bir seferde bir makina çalıştırılabilir, tek bir client için Gurobi kullanılacaksa bu lisans uygundur. Birden fazla client için ayrı ayrı cloud makinaları çalıştırılacaksa full lisans gereklidir. Ayrıntılı bilgi için: [http://www.gurobi.com/products/licensing-pricing/commercial-pricing#tab-3](http://www.gurobi.com/products/licensing-pricing/commercial-pricing#tab-3)

OR-Tools doğrudan bir solver değil, farklı solverları kullanmanıza aracı olan bir yazılım suiti olarak çalışıyor. Buna göre mevcut Markdown ve Transfer modelleri gibi, Mixed Integer Progamming(MIP) problemlerini çözdürebilmek için, OR-Tools'a SCIP, GLPK, Gurobi gibi 3. parti solverlar yükleyebiliyorsunuz. OR-Tools default olarak, yine açık kaynaklı olan [Coin-or branch and cut (CBC)](https://projects.coin-or.org/Cbc) solver'ını kullanıyor. Biz de şu anda, OR-Tools ile problemleri çözmek istediğimizde bu solver'ı kullanmış olacağız.

Şimdiye kadar tüm müşterilerin modelleri Gurobi sunucusundaki tek bir kuyruğa girip sırasını bekliyordu. Tek bir Gurobi lisansımız olduğu ve optimizasyon kullanan müşteri&proje sayısı artmaya devam ettiği için, burada bir darboğaz oluşuyor ve örneğin A müşterisindeki MD modelinin çözümü uzun sürdüğünde, B müşterisindeki TRN modeli onu beklemek zorunda kalıyordu. Artık, müşterilerin modelleri Gurobi'ye göndermeden, kendi sunucularındaki GoogleOR Tool ile çözme alternatifi var. Bu sayede, farklı müşterilerin modellerinin birbirinin önüne geçmemesi ve aynı anda, kendi içlerinde çalışabilmesi esnekliğini kazanıyoruz. Şunu ifade etmekte yarar var: Bu yapı bize müşteriler arasında paralellik kazandırıyor; ancak, bir müşteri için tüm modellerin (veya birden fazlasının) paralelde çözülmesi şu anda söz konusu değil, uygulama tek bir "thread" üzerinden ilerliyor. Bu nedenle modellerin tekil çözüm süreleri, ilgili müşterideki run'ın toplam süresi için önemli olmaya devam ediyor.

This document explains the details of the architecture of a system, that we named as Gurobi solver service. In this system, optimization problems are generated by MAPS algorithm applications (e.g markdown optimization, transfer optimization), and these problems are retrieved and solved by solver service applications hosted in a dedicated linux server. Our current Gurobi license (single machine, multi use) enables us to use this license in multiple applications. Therefore, we run applications concurrently and they optimize different problems in parallel. The number of the solver applications can be extended to any value but since all applications use the same system resources, it is now limited to eight.

### Motivation

Solver Service heavily use Amazon Web Services and Redis. In the previous structure of the solver service, clients are expected to have permission to Solver Manager Queue(AWS-SQS) and Redis-Gurobidirectly in order to make an optimization request. This API aims to simplify these requirements for the clients to some extent. Now, clients are only need to access the “secret service” whichever the cloud provider they are using(e.g. AWS, Azure).

Now, clients should also upload the *.mps* and *.prm* files to AWS S3 bucket *invent-gurobi-optimization-problems*. By the completion of the  , it is aimed to be cloud agnostic and clients will be able to use Azure Blob for using solver service.

### Endpoints

#### make_optimization_request

- POST optimization request data to https://solverservice.api.inventanalytics.com/prod/optimization_request/
- Validates optimization request data. If any problem, returns statusCode: 400, error and error type
- Send ModelInputFile section of the request data to redis with the key -model-info
- Send request to solver manager queue (sqs)
- Send heartbeat to redis

#### get_request_status

info
- Send request to solver manager queue (sqs)
- Send heartbeat to redis

#### get_request_status

- GET status with request id: https://solverservice.api.inventanalytics.com/prod/request_status/ with the query string parameters request_id=some-uuidhttps://solverservice.api.inventanalytics.com/prod/request_status/?request_id=some-uuid
- returns one of the three different status:COMPLETED: .sol file found in the storage serviceIn this case additionally “model_output_info” is returned in the response body. It contains the output file related information from ModelInputFile section that is posted while making optimization request. Solution file is expected to be downloaded by using the CloudServiceProvider, OutputFileStorageRoot and OutputFilePathRUNNING: no .sol file found but there is a heartbeat on redis or request is in gurobi queueNOT_FOUND: no heartbeat on redis, request id is not in gurobi queue and no .sol file found

#### cleanup_request

- returns an object with the field is_deleted which is True if the model info with the request id is deleted, False if it didn’t exist before calling the endpoint.

## Intro

[Gurobi](https://www.gurobi.com/) is a commercial software for solving complex optimization problems. It is installed and used on a single machine(7/24 up-and-running server), due to licensing limitations. For this reason, it may not be easy to debug the Gurobi service application and make development on it. This document aims to explain the development cycle of the Gurobi application.

The SolverService project is written in C# and located in MapsUnified as Maps.SolverService;

### 3- Redis

> Info: Redis documentation can be found here.

Redis is an in-memory data cache and is utilized in Solver Service to store optimization model’s heartbeat as well as the logistics of model and solution files.  The services working on the model try to update the heartbeat and clients can check this heartbeat to determine if a request is still being processed or not.

beat and clients can check this heartbeat to determine if a request is still being processed or not.

Redis can be accessed by various [tools](https://redis.io/resources/tools/). In this guide, `redis-cli` is preferred, which is included in the local redis [installation](https://redis.io/docs/getting-started/). Before going any further, it’s best to ping the redis server to see if it’s up.

- Connect to gurobi redis server by providing host option. (port is default 6379):

```bash
redis-cli -h gurobi.redis.prod.inventanalytics.com
```

- Then, send a ping signal. If redis service is healthy, it is expected to send a PONG back:

```
gurobi.redis.prod.inventanalytics.com:6379> ping
PONG
```

For each optimization request, a record in the following format is kept in Redis:`{request-id}-model-info`. Query this record to see if there’s anything unexpected:

```
gurobi.redis.prod.inventanalytics.com:6379> get 72f4732b-62c5-4fcd-8308-3e2e69474fed-model-info
```

gurobi.redis.prod.inventanalytics.com:6379> get 72f4732b-62c5-4fcd-8308-3e2e69474fed-model-info
```

As a result, you should see a record as such:

```
"{\"CloudServiceProvider\": \"aws\", \"InputFileBucketName\": null, \"InputFilePath\": \"72f4732b-62c5-4fcd-8308-3e2e69474fed.mps\", \"InputFileStorageRoot\": \"invent-gurobi-optimization-problems-test\", \"InputParameterFilePath\": \"72f4732b-62c5-4fcd-8308-3e2e69474fed.prm\", \"OutputFileBucketName\": null, \"OutputFilePath\": \"72f4732b-62c5-4fcd-8308-3e2e69474fed.sol\", \"OutputFileStorageRoot\": \"invent-gurobi-optimization-problems-test\"}"
```

> Note: If you don’t use the API, then your optimization request should also be present in redis with the key format {request-id}-data. This key is deleted after the request has been solved. It’s possible to check this record until then or if the solution process fails.

content: In our company, the current serialization format, MessagePack, has exhibited limitations in read-write performance for our high-volume dictionary data, where tuples serve as keys. To address this, we aim to explore alternative serialization formats such as Pickle, Avro, JSON, UJSON, Cbor, Quickle, and Protobuf. The primary goal is to identify a format that significantly improves the speed of data reading while ensuring data safety, considering that reading performance takes precedence over writing performance in our workflow. Efficient data storage and retrieval are pivotal for our operations, especially as we handle large-scale dictionary data. Minor enhancements in serialization and deserialization speed can yield substantial gains in workflow efficiency and productivity. The motivation behind this research lies in optimizing our data handling processes to meet evolving demands and scale effectively

2. Serialization: We serialized each dataset using the serial- ization formats under evaluation, including Pickle, Avro, JSON, UJSON, Cbor, Quickle, and Protobuf. For each format, we serialized the datasets separately.
3. Deserialization: After serialization, we measured the time taken to deserialize each dataset using the same serialization formats.
4. Performance Measurement: We recorded the read and write times for each serialization format on both datasets. Additionally, we monitored memory usage and CPU utilization during serialization and deserialization processes.
5. Repetition and Averaging: To ensure robustness and reliability of results, we repeated the serialization and deserialization processes 10 times for each dataset and format. We then averaged the results to obtain representative performance metrics.

content: In assessing the performance of various serialization formats, we will focus on several key metrics. Deserialization time, indicative of the duration needed to transform serialized data into its original form, will be closely monitored. Lower deserialization times signify more efficient data retrieval and processing, crucial for enhancing overall system performance. Serialization time, on the other hand, will measure the efficiency of each format in encoding data for storage or transmission. Faster serialization times are preferred as they reduce processing overhead and enhance system responsiveness. Additionally, CPU utilization will be evaluated to gauge the percentage of processing capacity utilized during serialization and deserialization tasks. High CPU utilization may indicate resource-intensive operations, highlighting the need for optimization. Lastly, we will consider the size of the converted storage type, reflecting the space occupied by serialized data

1. Pickle: Exhibited exceptional speed in both serialization and deserialization, particularly with the randomly generated data. This format seems highly optimized for performance but does come with specific drawbacks, such as potential security risks and compatibility issues between different Python versions. Despite these, Pickle’s performance makes it a suitable choice for environments where data source and Python environment are controlled and secure.
2. UJSON: Performed commendably, providing a significant reduction in serialization and deserialization times com- pared to standard JSON. This aligns with its design goal of being a faster alternative to JSON, especially useful in scenarios where processing speed is crucial. However, the compromise on float precision might limit its use in applications that require high numerical accuracy.

metadata.title: Comparative Analysis of Data Serialization Formats for High-Volume Dictionary Data: A Performance Study

content:
promise on float precision might limit its use in applications that require high numerical accuracy.
3. Avro: While the largest file sizes were noted with Avro, it also showed substantially longer serialization and deserialization times. This might detract from its viability in performance-sensitive applications, though it could still be beneficial where robust schema evolution and language independence are required.
4. Protobuf: Demonstrated moderate performance but with better control over schema and type safety, making it useful in systems where data integrity is paramount. The need for schema might complicate its use in dynamic environments but provides advantages in structured settings. For our real sample payload it is impossible to write schema because for our sample payload for some keys we have different size of tuples and their types can be change. For this reason, Protobuf cannot be our choice.

# Order Balancing

## Problem Definition

Distribution centers have limited capacity and they can be overcrowded in the holiday season. They tend to add workforce for increasing the capacities. In order balancing, our aim is to use the empty capacity before the holiday season for the items we would like to send for the holidays. The specific setting assumes DC has some empty capacity.

Boots Requirements

Boots have capacity in terms of pack types. We assume that each item has a pack type (in reality, an item can have multiple pack types). The capacity is defined for DC - pack type; therefore each DC - pack type can be thought of as distinct problems. The capacity might be about volume / quantity / pack quantity. In the current implementation, we do not support multiple capacity types for a DC - pack type. Constraints can be minimum - maximum or both; type should be the same (weight/volume/quantity).

Second requirement is the store inbound constraint. Each store has a maximum capacity for inbound. In this constraint, everything is more connected since stores use the same distribution centers.

Due to the problem size and specifics of Boots data, we solved this problem in a sequential manner. Therefore, we decided to start with solving the DC outbound problem and then solving the store inbound assuming the effect on the DC outbound constraints would be minimal.

Our first model is on date - source - pack type level. Second one is item - destination level, only the dates where transfer occurs are considered. Third model is also on the item - destination level.

# Future Visibility

In future visibility, we simulate the next x days (simulation horizon) to give customer a sense of what is going to happen. It has targets, inventory, orders in store - product - date level. It uses the standard input files from the customer. The simulation horizon argument in config is critical for the length of the simulation. Also we should have a long forecast (horizon + max cover period + max look ahead) from Noob in the vectorized form.

First task is scope generation. Scope generation is mostly similar to rocket_pandas. Differently, we create scope for all the pairs which are active in the simulation horizon and it also has a date dimension. It is expanded, all pairs exist for all dates. Also give_order flag is added via order_schedule, which shows which dates we are ordering for that pair. Order schedule and scope should be inline with the horizon

- scope
- order_schedule
- shipment_types

In cover period forecast, we have some of the functionalities in rocket_pandas. Lookahead is implemented. Stockout correction is not implemented since we do not know about the inventories for each date beforehand. Vectorized forecast is used for the algorithms.
